<br>
A rogue fits nicely in that setting, he needs both of these classes and he is doing pretty nice damage for the group.<br>
<br>
A wizard fits in too, but does not provide as much damage over time.<br>
<br>
Both of the classes can benefit from an enchanter and/or a bard.<br>
<br>
The real problem is that if you already have a dungeon crawl core group (warrior, cleric and an enchanter) adding melee classes increases group's damage output much more than adding wizard. In a NORMAL xp group rogues stack pretty well if the warrior knows where his taunt button is and uses it. Wizards stack too, but stack of rogues will grind through more mobs in an hour. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/umarktodd.showPublicProfile?language=EN>MarkTodd</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br>  Posts: 49<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/21/01 11:53 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Rogues, Wizards, and Damage</span><hr size=1> &quot;Wizards are second to none when it comes to casting powerful offensive spells. Certainly, other magic users are proficient in their own areas, but the wizard is most effective in battle. That is, as long as they have someone very sturdy to protect them from melee attacks.&quot;<br>
