That was not only rude, it was intentionally misleading.  Nowhere in my post did I EVER even remotely IMPLY that I didn't like epic-wielding level 60 Wizards.  What I DID say is that I was displeased with said epic-wielding level 60 Wizards who apparently forgot about the previous sixty levels and don't remember that not everyone has an uberguild, not everyone has a huge raid party around them to soak up aggro, and not everyone has level 60 spells.  Telling me you can drop x monster with a few Sunstrikes (as you said) is like telling a level 20 Wizards to stop bitching about Force Strike because Ice Comet is so good.<br>
<br>
Problems are problems at the level you face them, they are not solved by some remote single level that has x thing in it.  It's the same lame, stupid crap when people would say &quot;Wizards are fine, you can do 1000 damage with Ice Comet!!!!&quot;  Yeah... after 48 OTHER levels.<br>
<br>
&quot;I was talking about grouping, Grim. I'm pretty sure the whole post was about the level of dependency melee types have on others in the group to do their job.&quot;<br>
<br>
Well, Beryl, lets look at the post you put up.<br>
<br>
&quot;Can a 60 level rogue kill a blue? No. Can a 60 level wiz kill a blue? Yes, easily.&quot;<br>
<br>
So you were not referring to the Wizard soloing here?<br>
<br>
See, the point is, let's talk about grouping, not soloing.  That's the point, there are many Wizards here who are trying to pretend Wizards NEVER EVER need anyone around them, you can do it all alone!  A Wizard is the equal of a rogue/warrior/cleric!  And that is just not true, and you all know it.  Don't GO there.<br>
<br>
==============================================================<br>
<br>
&quot;One thing that is a source of irritation is when folks keep posting that bla,bla...is how such-and-such was originally intended. <br>
<br>
Well, how would anyone know? Do they work for VI? Please don't drag out the original Wizard description or any hack-garbage from Beta.&quot;<br>
<br>
We know becuase verant TOLD us what their intent and design was, in responses to our questions and emails and posts on message boards.  We aren't making this up, we are going on what we were TOLD by Verant.<br>
<br>
You don't like people talking about the description?  Too bad, the description was written to define and tell you what a class was like so when you created a character you'd have some idea what you were getting into.  See, the release didn't HAVE cheat and info sites everywhere with detailed spdat info on every spell.  You didn't even have full descriptions of spells in the book that came with Everquest originally, and it only went to level 29.  Your spells had a simple description on them: Mana cost, type of spell, name.  That tells you virtually nothing about the spells.<br>
<br>
So by looking through the book you saw a bunch of blasts (without the damage listed, resistance types, etc), a description that said MASTERS OF MAGICAL DAMAGE WITH NO RIVALS and MASTERS OF SEEKING KNOWLEDGE.  Gee, and people were stupid enough to think that might be true huh?<br>
<br>
Oh, and the reason people bring up Beta is that in Beta the Wizard class was a lot closer to that description than it is now.  In fact, they went too far making Wizards the masters of Magical Damage, it was absurd.  But the point is this: Verant had a design concept and class structure that they built and refined.  The original draft was too potent so they weakened it.  A lot.  Enormously.  To the point there are those idiotic levels like when Clerics can blast harder than Wizards, when Whirling Wind does nearly double the damage a Wizard blast does, that sort of thing.  Whether this was out of intent or being kind of sloppy and not looking closely at the other classes when they stripped Wizards back, I can't say.<br>
<br>
But the fact is, Verant tuned Wizards back heavily.  Then IN RESPONSE and INTENTIONALLY TO COMPENSATE for this, Verant gave Wizards sight spells and ports.  How do we know this?  Well GZ and others at Verant told us that was why we got the spells, and that this was the intent of the spells.  GZ also said the sight spells didn't work out like he inteneded and recognized ports don't help much in groups.  Further, with the release of Kunark and Velious, the evacs, the only grouping benefit of ports, were eroded to the point of being nothing (in Velious).<br>
<br>
This tells us two things:<br>
<br>
1) Verant thought Wizards needed compensation and something to balance the class.<br>
2) It didn't work.<br>
<br>
That leaves us with one conclusion:<br>
<br>
Verant intended us to be more balanced and needs to work on it, and they KNOW it. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ugrimstafftheurgist.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Grimstaff Theurgist</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://www,kestrelarts.com/images/book.jpg BORDER=0> at: 5/22/01 7:30:24 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ufazdaar00.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Fazdaar00</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/22/01 9:23 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Rogues, Wizards, and Damage</span><hr size=1> Umm, everyone of you who is saying that we don't need tanks and clerics to do our damage, try forming a single pull Sebilis group w/o a warrior, rogue, monk or cleric. 'Nough said. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/unatanmagus.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Natan Magus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br>  Posts: 57<br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/22/01 9:52 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Rogues, Wizards, and Damage</span><hr size=1> &quot;At some levels there are problems between wizard DD's and mage DD's, but who cares. The game isn't about being level 34-39 or where ever the problem lies.&quot;<br>
